The [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) [[World Heritage Site]]s are places of importance to [[cultural heritage|cultural]] or [[natural heritage]] as described in the UNESCO World Heritage Convention, established in 1972.<ref name=convention>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/convention/ |title=The World Heritage Convention |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> [[Italy]] ratified the convention on June 23, 1978, making its historical sites eligible for inclusion on the list.<ref name="italy"/> As of 2018, Italy has a total of 54 inscribed properties, making it the state party with the most World Heritage Sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list//en/news/1049/en/list&order=country|title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre - World Heritage List|first=UNESCO World Heritage|last=Centre|website=whc.unesco.org}}</ref>

Sites in Italy were first inscribed on the list at the 3rd Session of the [[World Heritage Committee]], held in [[Cairo]] and [[Luxor]], [[Egypt]] in 1979. At that session, one site was added: the "[[Rock Drawings in Valcamonica]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/archive/repcom79.htm#94 |title= Report of the Rapporteur|publisher=UNESCO |date=November 30, 1979 |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> A total of 25 (approximately half), of all Italian sites were added during the 1990s (where it was a member of the World Heritage Committee for the entire decade) with 10 sites added at the 21st session held in [[Naples]], Italy in 1997. Italy has served as a member of the World Heritage Committee four times, specifically, 1978-1985 (8 years), 1987-1993 (7 years), 1993-1999 (7 years), and 1999-2001 (3 years).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/it|title=Italy - UNESCO World Heritage Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|last=Centre|website=whc.unesco.org}}</ref>

Out of Italy's 54 heritage sites, five are shared with other countries: "[[Monte San Giorgio]]" and "[[Rhaetian Railway]] in the Albula / Bernina Landscapes" with Switzerland; "Historic Centre of Rome" with the [[Holy See|Vatican]]; "[[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps]]" with [[Austria]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Slovenia]] and [[Switzerland]]; and "[[Venetian Works of Defence between 15th and 17th centuries: Stato da Terra – western Stato da Mar]] with [[Croatia]] and [[Montenegro]]. Five World Heritage Sites in Italy are of the natural type, all others are cultural sites (49). Therefore, Italy has the largest number of world "cultural" heritage sites followed by Spain with 41 cultural sites.<ref name=italy/>

==World Heritage Sites==
The table lists information about each World Heritage Site:
:'''Name''': as listed by the World Heritage Committee<ref name=list>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list |title=World Heritage List |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref>
:'''Location''': city and region of site
:'''Area''': size of property and buffer zone
:'''UNESCO data''': the site's reference number; the year the site was inscribed on the World Heritage List; the criteria it was listed under: criteria ''i'' through ''vi'' are cultural, while ''vii'' through ''x'' are natural; ''(the column sorts by year added to the list)''
:'''Description''': brief description of the site
:'''The exhibition''': [http://www.unescosites.com A multi-sensory itinerary through the rich cultural and artistic heritage of the country, which recreates the atmosphere of some of the most fascinating places, recognized as a World Heritage Site.]

